jj345 19-Mar-20 09:43 PM
This course will enable you to construct and implement a personal career plan aligned with your preferred professional sector Four core topics will develop your career planning and career development skills: Global Employment Trends and Opportunities Career Planning and Decision Making Developing Future-Facing Graduate Competencies Effective Self-Presentation and Career Narratives Each topic has resources and activities targeted to improve your career thinking, market awareness, job-hunting skills and so improve your graduate career success. The more activities you engage with, the more you will get out of the micro-module. To encourage you to explore and get the benefit of all four topics, we will award a Career Futures Certificate of Completion recorded on your degree transcript if you complete a series of activities to the required level. You will find these completion requirements in each of the core topics and at the end of the micro-module.
From the module page

Dear all,(edited)
I’m writing to you on behalf of the EMFSS team at the LSE, and hope this email finds you well at such a turbulent period around the globe.   We recognise that the implications of Covid-19 have meant that this has been an uncertain time as you and your students approach this year’s examinations. We are also aware of the effort that you, your colleagues and your students have put into teaching and learning this year, in particular, moving to online or remote teaching over the past weeks.   Please be assured that the upcoming assessment period is at the forefront of our minds and we have been working closely with the University of London on contingency planning for the examinations. It has been our priority that whatever decision we make is as fair as possible for students and Teaching Centres around the world.   After careful deliberation and many hours of discussion with Academic Coordinators and key staff both from LSE and UOL, it is clear that it is no longer possible to run the EMFSS examinations as originally scheduled.   It is therefore our intention that examinations will take place instead in July/August 2020. Both LSE and UOL know that in some countries this may not be feasible due to Government policies or guidelines. In such cases we will do all we can to ensure that affected students have alternative arrangements. Students will receive official correspondence from UOL later today. We would appreciate your discretion until this is sent.   LSE and UOL are currently in discussion regarding contingency planning for students’ academic progression to minimise disruption to the student journey. We realise that it takes considerable determination for students to successfully complete an EMFSS degree, and I trust that you will appreciate that we are seeking to balance the interests of the entire community of students and EMFSS Teaching Centres.

Trikkur 30-Apr-20 09:46 PM
I am not sure I am the best person to answer these questions and I mean no offense to anyone. I am quite young for my educational level. I have been moving my whole life. I have been to ten different schools in four cities. I have done 5 different educational boards. I was homeschooled during my 7th and 8th grade. Other than that I went to a 'normal' school. So, this is not my first time studying independently. The main reason I took this route, was because I planned to do other courses along with this. People I meet find it odd that I am not in an 'actual' university. They think it is weird that I don't have the 'uni experiences' as you put it. And, yes, sometimes I do wish I went to a regular college. But, the fact remains that QUALITY self-study is better than any other form. If your command of English is quite good, you can understand anything if you put your mind to it. It is an opportunity to do as much as you can. You may actually end up studying at a faster pace than if you were taught at an educational institution. Those who opt for the 'normal' university, might get the experience but they cant do everything else they could have accomplished in that time. I am doing BSc Economics third year, Institute and Faculty of Actuaries (Core Subjects), CIMA (Cert. BA), Indian Chartered Accountancy. And I plan to complete all of that (hopefully). I feel that networking with colleagues is good but not essential. The benefits of studying independently outweigh the costs (in my opinion). Plus, there is much more time than most think to Network (Though again, truth be told, I don't think I am qualified to answer on that aspect).

I could do with some tips & tricks what I should concentrate on in this subject.
@locknload Make sure you're comfortable with all the financial statement formats and some complexities that are common in the past paper questions such as bad debt provision, depreciation etc. If you can prepare IS, S of FP and statement of changes in equity, youre good to go for the first question. For financial accounting, the two other questions are usually about cash flow statement and ratio analysis. While for management accounting, the questions are usually about either variance calculations, NPV, IRR, ARR calculation or cash budget preparation or absorption and marginal costing. So make sure you can complete atleast one of these questions
